Rudzani Matshili As the world commemorates World  Aids Day tomorrow, the South African National Defence Force (SANDF) this morning staged its HIV/Aids awareness drive in solidarity with the international community’s shared vision of zero new infections, zero discrimination and zero Aids-related deaths. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  December 1 every year, is dedicated to raising awareness of the Aids pandemic caused by the spread of HIV infection and mourning those who have died of the disease. This year, the day will be commemorated under the theme: “I have the right to know my status, prevention is my responsibility.” The Surgeon General of the SANDF, Lieutenant General Aubrey Sedibe who delivered a keynote address to the soldiers at Pretoria Military Sports Club (PMSC) in Thaba Tshwane, encouraged them to get tested and know their status. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  The address was followed by a health fun walk through the streets of Thaba Tshwane and ended off by voluntary HIV Testing at the sports club. Awareness sporting activities were conducted as ways to communicate HIV/Aids prevention message.